            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Marcus Jin Lee was born not in a hospital, but in the small apartment above his parents\u2019 Cantonese restaurant in the Inner Richmond. His childhood was a symphony of clattering woks, the sharp scent of ginger, and the unspoken expectation that he would one day take over the family business. A quiet, introspective boy, Marcus found his voice not in conversation but in the charcoal sketches he secretly made in his notebooks. For him, art was a language more honest than words.\n\nHis father\u2019s sudden death from a heart attack when Marcus was 19 was the turning point. The grief was a suffocating silence in their family, a void no one knew how to fill. It was in this profound loss that Marcus realized his calling: to help others articulate the inarticulable. He respectfully declined his inheritance of the restaurant, instead enrolling at SF State and later pursuing a graduate degree from the California Institute of Integral Studies, focusing on Expressive Arts Therapy.\n\nNow 54, Marcus runs a successful private practice from a serene, light-filled office in Laurel Heights. His 2.8-mile bicycle commute from his Inner Sunset home is a daily meditation, a way to connect with the city's rhythm. His clients are teachers, nurses, and social workers\u2014people whose own emotional reserves are often depleted. He doesn\u2019t offer easy answers; instead, he provides clay, paint, and a safe space for them to shape their own understanding.\n\nMarcus shares his life with his partner of 22 years, Alex, a public-school librarian. Their evenings are spent walking through Golden Gate Park or cooking together, a comfortable rhythm built on shared values. Having watched San Francisco transform through booms and busts, Marcus feels a deep, protective connection to its soul. His dream isn't expansion but depth: he hopes to begin mentoring young therapists and launching a free art therapy workshop for at-risk youth. He wants to give back to the city that, for all its changes, remains the only canvas he has ever called home."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe remembers being nine, hiding beneath the stainless-steel prep table in the kitchen. The air was thick with the scent of ginger and his father\u2019s booming voice calling his name. Outside, the restaurant hummed with orders. But under the table, with a stolen piece of charcoal and a paper napkin, he was miles away, sketching the curve of a seagull\u2019s wing. It was a moment of pure, secret freedom\u2014a silent rebellion that taught him art was his truest escape, his most honest language.\n\n2.\nAt 19, a week after his father\u2019s funeral, he stood in the doorway of the silent kitchen. The woks were cold, the cleavers still. His mother moved like a shadow, the usual kitchen symphony replaced by a suffocating emptiness. That silence was more deafening than any noise had ever been. It was in that moment, feeling the immense weight of grief with no words to hold it, that he understood his life's purpose wouldn't be filling plates, but helping people navigate the silent, hollow spaces within themselves.\n\n3.\nHe was 32, walking with Alex through the AIDS Memorial Grove. It was a quiet Tuesday, the fog soft and heavy around them. They hadn't spoken for nearly ten minutes, simply listening to the hush of the trees. Then, Alex reached over and took his hand, a simple, firm pressure. In that silent, unassuming gesture, Marcus felt a profound sense of being seen and anchored. It wasn\u2019t a grand declaration, but a quiet promise of shared space that has defined their life together ever since.\n\n4.\nIn his late 30s, a young teacher came to his practice, overwhelmed and unable to speak about her burnout. Marcus simply placed a large block of gray clay in front of her. For a full session, she just squeezed and twisted it, her knuckles white. Finally, she looked at the gnarled shape in her hands, tears welling in her eyes, and whispered, \"It's so heavy.\" The breakthrough wasn\u2019t in finding a solution, but in giving the feeling a physical form. It affirmed his entire philosophy.\n\n5.\nJust last year, at 53, while biking home through the Panhandle, he saw a teenager spray-painting a vibrant, chaotic mural on a boarded-up wall. He didn't see vandalism; he saw a desperate, beautiful need to be seen. He saw himself, a boy hiding under a table with a piece of charcoal. The sight filled him not with judgment, but with an urgent sense of purpose. It was the moment his vague dream of a youth workshop became a concrete, necessary mission."
